│ stop({"edit_points": [[3329, 3331, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp"]],     │
│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe LLVM `loop-vectorize` pass is crashing  │
│ with an assertion failure when processing a loop containing a first-order recurrence on a  │
│ non-power-of-two integer type (`i24`). The crash occurs within the cost model,             │
│ specifically when trying to calculate the cost of a `VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe`. The │
│ assertion `isa<VectorType>(Val)` fails, indicating that the code incorrectly assumes a     │
│ `Type*` is a `VectorType*`.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace shows the     │
│ crash happens in `VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost`, which is called by        │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::emitInvalidCostRemarks`. This is significant because it means   │
│ the vectorizer has already decided that vectorization is not beneficial and is merely      │
│ trying to report *why*. The crash during the cost-analysis-for-remarks phase prevents the  │
│ pass from completing and reporting the reason for not vectorizing.\n\nThe Scalar Evolution │
│ analysis correctly identifies the loop's trip count and classifies the recurrence PHI      │
│ (`%for`) as `Variant`, which is expected. The issue is not in the analysis phase but in    │
│ the subsequent cost modeling phase.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy inspecting the     │
│ source code of `VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost`, the exact point of failure  │
│ can be identified. The function attempts to calculate the cost of the vector shuffle       │
│ needed to handle the first-order recurrence.\n\nThe relevant code snippet is:\n```cpp\n//  │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n\nunsigned                                 │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost(...) const {\n  // ...\n  Type *VectorTy =    │
│ VectorType::get(Phi->getType(), EC);\n  // ...\n  auto *ShufTy = cast<VectorType>(\n       │
│ VTT.getVectorType(Phi->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits()));\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n1.         │
│ `Phi->getType()` returns `i24`.\n2.  `VectorType::get(Phi->getType(), EC)` correctly       │
│ creates a vector type like `<4 x i24>`.\n3.  The problematic line is                       │
│ `VTT.getVectorType(Phi->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits())`.\n    *                         │
│ `Phi->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits()` returns `24`.\n    *   `VTT.getVectorType(24)` is  │
│ called. `VectorTypeUtils` (`VTT`) is designed to work with legal, power-of-two bitwidths.  │
│ When asked for a vector type for a 24-bit scalar, it cannot find a legal vector register   │
│ type and returns the scalar type `i24` itself as a fallback.\n    *   The result, an       │
│ `IntegerType*` (for `i24`), is then passed to `cast<VectorType>`.\n4.  The                 │
│ `cast<VectorType>` fails because the type is `i24` (an `IntegerType`), not a `VectorType`, │
│ triggering the assertion.\n\nThe fundamental issue is that the cost model for first-order  │
│ recurrences does not correctly handle cases where the underlying scalar type is a          │
│ non-power-of-two integer, for which `VectorTypeUtils` cannot produce a valid vector        │
│ type.\n\nThe fix is to check if `VTT.getVectorType()` actually returns a `VectorType`      │
│ before attempting to cast and use it. If it does not, we should assume a high cost, as     │
│ vectorization of this operation is not supported, which aligns with the function's purpose │
│ of cost estimation.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix involves adding a check to │
│ validate the type returned by `VTT.getVectorType` before the `cast` in                     │
│ `VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost`.\n\n**File**:                               │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n// Edit Point 1:\n// In        │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost, add a check for the\n// returned type.\n\n// │
│ The shuffle is performed on a vector of the same type as the phi,\n// but with the         │
│ bitwidth rounded up to the next power of two.\nauto *ShufTy =\n                            │
│ VTT.getVectorType(Phi->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits());\nif (!isa<VectorType>(ShufTy))\n │
│ return TTI.getImpossibleCost();\nauto *ShufVTy = cast<VectorType>(ShufTy);\nreturn         │
│ TTI.getShuffleCost(\n    {TargetTransformInfo::SK_Permute, ShufVTy, 0,                     │
│ nullptr});\n```\n\nThis change is applied around line 3329 in                              │
