│ // returned type.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ // The shuffle is performed on a vector of the same type as the phi,                       │
│ // but with the bitwidth rounded up to the next power of two.                              │
│ auto *ShufTy =                                                                             │
│     VTT.getVectorType(Phi->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits());                              │
│ if (!isa<VectorType>(ShufTy))                                                              │
│   return TTI.getImpossibleCost();                                                          │
│ auto *ShufVTy = cast<VectorType>(ShufTy);                                                  │
│ return TTI.getShuffleCost(                                                                 │
│     {TargetTransformInfo::SK_Permute, ShufVTy, 0, nullptr});                               │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ This fix is for a different version of the code. I need to adapt it to the version I have. │
│                                                                                            │
│ In my version, the call is `Ctx.TTI.getShuffleCost(TargetTransformInfo::SK_Splice,         │
│ cast<VectorType>(VectorTy), ...)`. `VectorTy` is `<VF x i24>`.                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that `i24` is not a legal type for vector operations on many targets. The   │
│ TTI implementation likely tries to find a legal vector type to perform the shuffle on,     │
│ fails for `i24`, returns a scalar type, and then a `cast` inside `getShuffleCost` fails.   │
│                                                                                            │
